 blocks of the universe—time, gravity, light, and elementary particles—and chemistry’s ability to explain the interactions among them. Scott, with the assistance of James Lawrence Powell, next tours the earth and atmospheric sciences to explain the forces that shape our planet and then takes off for the stars to describe our place in the cosmos. He provides vivid introductions to our collective scientific inheritance, narrating discoveries such as the shape of the atom and the nature of the nucleus or how we use GPS to measure time and what that has to do with relativity. A clear demonstration of the power of scientific reasoning to bring the incomprehensible within our grasp, The Universe as It Really Is gives an engrossing account of just how much we do understand about the world around us.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCosmic physics. 0aGravitational fields. 0aMeteorology. 0aSpace sciences. 7aSCIENCE / Philosophy & Social Aspects.2bisacsh1 aPowell, James.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060660708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018 Englishz978311060425208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018z9783110603255oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Medicine and Life Sciences 2018 Englishz978311060420708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Medicine and Life Sciences 2018z9783110603200oZDB-23-DPM40uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/scot1849440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231545761423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780231545761.jpg  a978-3-11-060420-7  EBOOK PACKAGE Medicine and Life Sciences 2018 Englishb2018  a978-3-11-060425-2  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018 Englishb2018